description: A warm-hearted and funny fish-out-of-water romantic comedy by J. Torres and Eric Kim, Love as a Foreign Language raises the bar for American manga. Joel, a Canadian English-teacher working in a second language school in Korea, has finally had his fill of foreign lands. He’s tried his best to avoid assimilation of Korean culture, stubbornly refusing to learn more than the rudimentary basics of the language, and fearing any unfamiliar foods. His decision to go back to Canada is thwarted, however, when he becomes smitten with a beautiful comics-reading secretary named Hana who works at the second language school. Unfortunately for Joel, his awkwardness at negotiating the cultural currents hinders his relationship with Hana, often with hilarious results. Along the way, Joel discovers that the language of love can be as difficult to learn as any other.
name: Love As A Foreign Language

description:
Proper Japanese Title: 無限の住人

Japanese publication, has been translated in English by Dark Horse (Blade of the Immortal), German by Ehapa Verlag (Blade of the Immortal), French by Casterman (L'Habitant de L'Infini), Spanish by Glénat (La Espada del Inmortal), Polish by Egmont (Miecz Nieśmiertelnego), Italian by Panini (L'Immortale), Greek by Anubis Comics (Blade of the Immortal), Portuguese by Editora Conrad (Blade - A Lâmina do Imortal), Chinese by both Comics World (Wú Xiàn Zhī Zhù Rén) and Youth Comics Series (Wú Xiàn Zhù Rén), and Norwegian by Schibsted (Blade den Udødelige). The series was also partially translated into Swedish by Full Stop Media in a manga anthology, but the series was dropped after only six issues and replaced with Puppet Revolution (Manga Mania).

Despite it being referred to as Blade of the Immortal in most countries, the name actually translates to The Inhabitant of Infinity, a title which is carried over to the French adaptation only.

Starring Thomas Wayne as Batman, Brian Azzarello and Eduardo Risso produced this limited series as a tie-in to Flashpoint. It proved to be the best selling of the many Flashpoint tie-ins.

Plot Summary

In a timeline where young Bruce Wayne died in the infamous Crime Alley, his father Thomas went on to private Gotham City's law enforcement and secretly become Batman while his mother Martha lost her mind and became the psychotic Joker. After learning from Barry Allen that there was a way to restore a timeline where Bruce survived, Thomas has his final confrontation with his estranged and dangerous wife, seeking her approval to save their son at the expense of their own lives.

deck: The second Phantom series publication volume V20 by Indrajal Comics.
description:
The editors of Indrajal Comics earlier published a self-titled series in India to issue #443. In 1983 the publishers decided to use a volume and number typical of periodical publications starting with the 2nd January 1983 issue. Hence, #444 was identified as Vol.20 No.1 on the cover as the new starting series number and #805 (Vol.27 No.8 published on 16 April 1990) was the last. The front cover design was also changed (starting with issue #789 Vol.26 No.33), with the introduction of the distinctive Indrajal Comics banner. Some issues were reprints of older stories from the previous Indrajal Comics Volume, with new cover art.

Like the previous series, The Phantom dominated the number of stories, but characters like Mandrake, Flash Gordon, Bahadur, Kerry Drake, Rip Kirby, Phil Corrigan, Garth, Mike Nomad, Buz Sawyer, Bruce Lee, Aditya and Dara also had stories presented.

Related Items

  • Indrajal Comics Volume 1
name: Indrajal Comics
